# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: emc-design-embedded
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] In electronics, a **choke** is an inductor used to block higher-frequency alternating currents (AC) while passing direct current (DC) and lower-frequency ACs in a circuit.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] A choke usually consists of a coil of insulated wire often wound on a magnetic core, although some consist of a doughnut-shaped ferrite bead strung on a wire.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] The choke's impedance increases with frequency.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Its low electrical resistance passes both AC and DC with little power loss, but its reactance limits the amount of AC passed.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] The name comes from blocking—"choking"—high frequencies while passing low frequencies.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] It is a functional name; the name "choke" is used if an inductor is used for blocking or decoupling higher frequencies, but the component is simply called an "inductor" if used in electronic filters or tuned circuits.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Inductors designed for use as chokes are usually distinguished by not having low-loss construction (high Q factor) required in inductors used in tuned circuits and filtering applications.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Audio frequency chokes usually have ferromagnetic cores to increase their inductance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] They are often constructed similarly to transformers, with laminated iron cores and an air gap.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] The iron core increases the inductance for a given volume of the core.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Chokes were frequently used in the design of rectifier power supplies for vacuum tube equipment such as radio receivers or amplifiers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] They are commonly found in direct-current motor controllers to produce direct current (DC), where they were used in conjunction with large electrolytic capacitors to remove the voltage ripple (AC) at the output DC.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] A rectifier circuit designed for a choke-output filter may produce too much DC output voltage and subject the rectifier and filter capacitors to excessive in-rush and ripple currents if the inductor is removed.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] However, modern electrolytic capacitors with high ripple current ratings, and voltage regulators that remove more power supply ripple than chokes could, have eliminated heavy, bulky chokes from mains frequency power supplies.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Smaller chokes are used in switching power supplies to remove the higher-frequency switching transients from the output and sometimes from feeding back into the mains input.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Some car audio hobbyists use choke coils with automobile audio systems (specifically in the wiring of a subwoofer, to remove high frequencies from the amplified signal).
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Radio frequency chokes (RFC) often have iron powder or ferrite cores which increases inductance and overall operation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] They are often wound in complex patterns (basket winding) to reduce self-capacitance and proximity effect losses.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Chokes for even higher frequencies have non-magnetic cores and low inductance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] A modern form of choke used for eliminating digital RF noise from lines is the ferrite bead, a cylindrical or torus-shaped core of ferrite slipped over a wire.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] These are often seen on computer cables.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] A common-mode (CM) choke is a special application where a choke is used to act upon a common-mode signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] These chokes are useful for suppression of electromagnetic interference (EMI) and radio frequency interference (RFI) frequently introduced on high current wires such as on power supply lines, which may cause unwanted operation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Reducing this noise is frequently done by using a common mode choke—two parallel coil windings on a single core.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Common mode chokes allow differential currents to pass while blocking signals that are affecting both wires.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Because the magnetic flux produced by differential-mode currents in the core of a common mode choke tend to cancel each other out, the choke presents little impedance to differential mode currents.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] It achieves this by the placement of windings such that they generate equal but opposite fields that cancel each other out for differential mode signals.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] Normally this also means that the core will not saturate for large differential mode currents, and the maximum current rating is instead determined by the heating effect of the winding resistance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] On the other hand, common mode currents see a high impedance path due to the combined inductance of the windings that reinforce each other.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] CM chokes are commonly used in industrial, electrical and telecommunications applications to remove or decrease noise and related electromagnetic interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] When the CM choke is conducting CM current, most of the magnetic flux generated by the windings is confined within the inductor core because of its high permeability.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] In this case, the leakage flux, which is also the near magnetic field emission of the CM choke is low.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] However, the DM current flowing through the windings will generate high emitted near magnetic field since the windings are negative coupled in this case.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] To reduce the near magnetic field emission, a twisted winding structure can be applied to the CM choke.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] The difference between the balanced twisted windings CM choke and conventional balanced two winding CM choke is that the windings interact in the center of the core open window.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] When it is conducting CM current, the balanced twisted winding CM inductor can provide identical CM inductance as the conventional CM inductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/choke-electronics] When it is conducting DM current, the equivalent current loops will generate inversed direction magnetic fields in space so that they tend to cancel each other.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC pursues three main classes of issue.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Emission* is the generation of electromagnetic energy, whether deliberate or accidental, by some source and its release into the environment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC studies the unwanted emissions and the countermeasures which may be taken in order to reduce unwanted emissions.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The second class, *susceptibility*, is the tendency of electrical equipment, referred to as the victim, to malfunction or break down in the presence of unwanted emissions, which are known as radio-frequency interference (RFI).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] *Immunity* is the opposite of susceptibility, being the ability of equipment to function correctly in the presence of RFI, with the discipline of "hardening" equipment being known equally as susceptibility or immunity.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] A third class studied is *coupling*, which is the mechanism by which emitted interference reaches the victim.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Interference mitigation and hence electromagnetic compatibility may be achieved by addressing any or all of these issues, i.e., quieting the sources of interference, inhibiting coupling paths and/or hardening the potential victims.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In practice, many of the engineering techniques used, such as grounding and shielding, apply to all three issues.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The earliest EMC issue was lightning strike (lightning electromagnetic pulse, or LEMP) on ships and buildings.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Lightning rods or lightning conductors began to appear in the mid-18th century.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] With the advent of widespread electricity generation and power supply lines from the late 19th century on, problems also arose with equipment short-circuit failure affecting the power supply, and with local fire and shock hazard when the power line was struck by lightning.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Power stations were provided with output circuit breakers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Buildings and appliances would soon be provided with input fuses, and later in the 20th century miniature circuit breakers (MCB) would come into use.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] It may be said that radio interference and its correction arose with the first spark-gap experiment of Marconi in the late 1800s.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] As radio communications developed in the first half of the 20th century, interference between broadcast radio signals began to occur and an international regulatory framework was set up to ensure interference-free communications.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Switching devices became commonplace through the middle of the 20th century, typically in petrol powered cars and motorcycles but also in domestic appliances such as thermostats and refrigerators.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This caused transient interference with domestic radio and (after World War II) TV reception, and in due course laws were passed requiring the suppression of such interference sources.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge (ESD) problems first arose with accidental electric spark discharges in hazardous environments such as coal mines and when refuelling aircraft or motor cars.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Safe working practices had to be developed.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] After World War II the military became increasingly concerned with the effects of nuclear electromagnetic pulse (NEMP), lightning strike, and even high-powered radar beams, on vehicle and mobile equipment of all kinds, and especially aircraft electrical systems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] When high RF emission levels from other sources became a potential problem (such as with the advent of microwave ovens), certain frequency bands were designated for Industrial, Scientific and Medical (ISM) use, allowing emission levels limited only by thermal safety standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Later, the International Telecommunication Union adopted a Recommendation providing limits of radiation from ISM devices in order to protect radiocommunications.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] A variety of issues such as sideband and harmonic emissions, broadband sources, and the ever-increasing popularity of electrical switching devices and their victims, resulted in a steady development of standards and laws.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the late 1970s, the popularity of modern digital circuitry rapidly grew.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] As the technology developed, with ever-faster switching speeds (increasing emissions) and lower circuit voltages (increasing susceptibility), EMC increasingly became a source of concern.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Many more nations became aware of EMC as a growing problem and issued directives to the manufacturers of digital electronic equipment, which set out the essential manufacturer requirements before their equipment could be marketed or sold.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Organizations in individual nations, across Europe and worldwide, were set up to maintain these directives and associated standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1979, the American FCC published a regulation that required the electromagnetic emissions of all "digital devices" to be below certain limits.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This regulatory environment led to a sharp growth in the EMC industry supplying specialist devices and equipment, analysis and design software, and testing and certification services.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Low-voltage digital circuits, especially CMOS transistors, became more susceptible to ESD damage as they were miniaturised and, despite the development of on-chip hardening techniques, a new ESD regulatory regime had to be developed.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] From the 1980s on the explosive growth in mobile communications and broadcast media channels put huge pressure on the available airspace.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Regulatory authorities began squeezing band allocations closer and closer together, relying on increasingly sophisticated EMC control methods, especially in the digital communications domain, to keep cross-channel interference to acceptable levels.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Digital systems are inherently less susceptible than analogue systems, and also offer far easier ways (such as software) to implement highly sophisticated protection and error-correction measures.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 1985, the USA released the ISM bands for low-power mobile digital communications, leading to the development of Wi-Fi and remotely-operated car door keys.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This approach relies on the intermittent nature of ISM interference and use of sophisticated error-correction methods to ensure lossless reception during the quiet gaps between any bursts of interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC ensures the correct operation, in the same electromagnetic environment, of different equipment items which use or respond to electromagnetic phenomena, and the avoidance of any interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Another way of saying this is that EMC is the control of EMI so that unwanted effects are prevented.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Besides understanding the phenomena in themselves, EMC also addresses the countermeasures, such as control regimes, design and measurement, which should be taken in order to prevent emissions from causing any adverse effect.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMC is often understood as the control of electromagnetic interference (EMI).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electromagnetic interference divides into several categories according to the source and signal characteristics.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be man-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference comprises a given range of frequencies.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This type is naturally divided into sub-categories according to frequency range, and as a whole is sometimes referred to as "DC to daylight".
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] One common classification is into narrowband and broadband, according to the spread of the frequency range.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, is a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pulse signals divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] When a source emits interference, it follows a route to the victim known as the coupling path.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] There are four basic coupling mechanisms: conductive, capacitive, magnetic or inductive, and radiative.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Any coupling path can be broken down into one or more of these coupling mechanisms working together.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Source and victim act as radio antennas: the source emits or radiates an electromagnetic wave which propagates across the space in between and is picked up or received by the victim.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The damaging effects of electromagnetic interference pose unacceptable risks in many areas of technology, and it is necessary to control such interference and reduce the risks to acceptable levels.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The risk posed by the threat is usually statistical in nature, so much of the work in threat characterisation and standards setting is based on reducing the probability of disruptive EMI to an acceptable level, rather than its assured elimination.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] For a complex or novel piece of equipment, this may require the production of a dedicated *EMC control plan* summarizing the application of the above and specifying additional documents required.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Breaking a coupling path is equally effective at either the start or the end of the path, therefore many aspects of good EMC design practice apply equally to potential sources and to potential victims.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] A design which easily couples energy to the outside world will equally easily couple energy in and will be susceptible.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] A single improvement will often reduce both emissions and susceptibility.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Grounding and shielding aim to reduce emissions or divert EMI away from the victim by providing an alternative, low-impedance path.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Testing is required to confirm that a particular device meets the required standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] It is divided broadly into emissions testing and susceptibility testing.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Open-area test sites, or OATS, are the reference sites in most standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] They are especially useful for emissions testing of large equipment systems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] However, RF testing of a physical prototype is most often carried out indoors, in a specialized EMC test chamber.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Types of the chamber include anechoic, reverberation and the gigahertz transverse electromagnetic cell (GTEM cell).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Sometimes computational electromagnetics simulations are used to test virtual models.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Like all compliance testing, it is important that the test equipment, including the test chamber or site and any software used, be properly calibrated and maintained.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typically, a given run of tests for a particular piece of equipment will require an *EMC test plan* and a follow-up *test report*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The full test program may require the production of several such documents.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Emissions are typically measured for radiated field strength and where appropriate for conducted emissions along cables and wiring.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Inductive (magnetic) and capacitive (electric) field strengths are near-field effects and are only important if the device under test (DUT) is designed for a location close to other electrical equipment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] For conducted emissions, typical transducers include the LISN (line impedance stabilization network) or AMN (artificial mains network) and the RF current clamp.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] For radiated emission measurement, antennas are used as transducers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Typical antennas specified include dipole, biconical, log-periodic, double ridged guide and conical log-spiral designs.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated emissions must be measured in all directions around the DUT.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Specialized EMI test receivers or EMI analyzers are used for EMC compliance testing.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] These incorporate bandwidths and detectors as specified by international EMC standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] An EMI receiver may be based on a spectrum analyser to measure the emission levels of the DUT across a wide band of frequencies (frequency domain), or on a tunable narrower-band device which is swept through the desired frequency range.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] EMI receivers along with specified transducers can often be used for both conducted and radiated emissions.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Pre-selector filters may also be used to reduce the effect of strong out-of-band signals on the front-end of the receiver.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some pulse emissions are more usefully characterized using an oscilloscope to capture the pulse waveform in the time domain.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Radiated field susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered source of RF or EM energy and a radiating antenna to direct the energy at the potential victim or device under test (DUT).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Conducted voltage and current susceptibility testing typically involves a high-powered signal generator, and a current clamp or other type of transformer to inject the test signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Transient or EMP signals are used to test the immunity of the DUT against powerline disturbances including surges, lightning strikes and switching noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In motor vehicles, similar tests are performed on battery and signal lines.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The transient pulse may be generated digitally and passed through a broadband pulse amplifier, or applied directly to the transducer from a specialized pulse generator.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Electrostatic discharge testing is typically performed with a piezo spark generator called an "ESD pistol".
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Higher energy pulses, such as lightning or nuclear EMP simulations, can require a large current clamp or a large antenna which completely surrounds the DUT.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Some antennas are so large that they are located outdoors, and care must be taken not to cause an EMP hazard to the surrounding environment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Several organizations, both national and international, work to promote international co-operation on standardization (harmonization), including publishing various EMC standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Where possible, a standard developed by one organization may be adopted with little or no change by others.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] This helps for example to harmonize national standards across Europe.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with national or international standards is usually laid down by laws passed by individual nations.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Different nations can require compliance with different standards.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In European law, EU directive 2014/30/EU (previously 2004/108/EC) on EMC defines the rules for the placing on the market/putting into service of electric/electronic equipment within the European Union.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] The Directive applies to a vast range of equipment including electrical and electronic appliances, systems and installations.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Manufacturers of electric and electronic devices are advised to run EMC tests in order to comply with compulsory CE-labeling.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] More are given in the list of EMC directives.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] Compliance with the applicable harmonised standards whose reference is listed in the OJEU under the EMC Directive gives presumption of conformity with the corresponding essential requirements of the EMC Directive.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-compatibility] In 2019, the USA adopted a program for the protection of critical infrastructure against an electromagnetic pulse, whether caused by a geomagnetic storm or a high-altitude nuclear weapon.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Both human-made and natural sources generate changing electrical currents and voltages that can cause EMI: ignition systems, cellular network of mobile phones, lightning, solar flares, and auroras (northern/southern lights).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] It can also affect mobile phones, FM radios, and televisions, as well as observations for radio astronomy and atmospheric science.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] EMI can be used intentionally for radio jamming, as in electronic warfare.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Since the earliest days of radio communications, the negative effects of interference from both intentional and unintentional transmissions have been felt and the need to manage the radio frequency spectrum became apparent.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In 1933, a meeting of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC) in Paris recommended the International Special Committee on Radio Interference (CISPR) be set up to deal with the emerging problem of EMI.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] CISPR subsequently produced technical publications covering measurement and test techniques and recommended emission and immunity limits.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These have evolved over the decades and form the basis of much of the world's EMC regulations today.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In 1979, legal limits were imposed on electromagnetic emissions from all digital equipment by the FCC in the US in response to the increased number of digital systems that were interfering with wired and radio communications.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Test methods and limits were based on CISPR publications, although similar limits were already enforced in parts of Europe.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In the mid 1980s, the European Union member states adopted a number of "new approach" directives with the intention of standardizing technical requirements for products so that they do not become a barrier to trade within the EC.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] One of these was the EMC Directive (89/336/EC) and it applies to all equipment placed on the market or taken into service.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Its scope covers all apparatus "liable to cause electromagnetic disturbance or the performance of which is liable to be affected by such disturbance".
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This was the first time there was a legal requirement on immunity, as well as emissions on apparatus intended for the general population.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Although there may be additional costs involved for some products to give them a known level of immunity, it increases their perceived quality as they are able to co-exist with apparatus in the active EM environment of modern times and with fewer problems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Many countries now have similar requirements for products to meet some level of electromagnetic compatibility (EMC) regulation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The origin of interference, often called "noise" in this context, can be human-made (artificial) or natural.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Continuous, or continuous wave (CW), interference arises where the source continuously emits at a given range of frequencies.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] An electromagnetic pulse (EMP), sometimes called a transient disturbance, arises where the source emits a short-duration pulse of energy.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The energy is usually broadband by nature, although it often excites a relatively narrow-band *damped sine wave* response in the victim.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Sources divide broadly into isolated and repetitive events.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted electromagnetic interference is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI, which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic disturbances in the EM field of a conductor will no longer be confined to the surface of the conductor and will radiate away from it.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This persists in all conductors and mutual inductance between two radiated electromagnetic fields will result in EMI.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the technical terms which are employed can be used with differing meanings.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Some phenomena may be referred to by various different terms.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These terms are used here in a widely accepted way, which is consistent with other articles in the encyclopedia.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The basic arrangement of noise emitter or source, coupling path and victim, receptor or sink is shown in the figure below.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Source and victim are usually electronic hardware devices, though the source may be a natural phenomenon such as a lightning strike, electrostatic discharge (ESD) or, in one famous case, the Big Bang at the origin of the Universe.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] For example the lower path in the diagram involves inductive, conductive and capacitive modes.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Conductive coupling occurs when the coupling path between the source and victim is formed by direct electrical contact with a conducting body, for example a transmission line, wire, cable, PCB trace or metal enclosure.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling occurs where the source and victim are separated by a short distance (typically less than a wavelength).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Strictly, "Inductive coupling" can be of two kinds, electrical induction and magnetic induction.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] It is common to refer to electrical induction as *capacitive coupling*, and to magnetic induction as *inductive coupling*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Capacitive coupling occurs when a varying electrical field exists between two adjacent conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage on the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Inductive coupling or magnetic coupling occurs when a varying magnetic field exists between two parallel conductors typically less than a wavelength apart, inducing a change in voltage along the receiving conductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Radiative coupling or electromagnetic coupling occurs when source and victim are separated by a large distance, typically more than a wavelength.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This is also a definition used by the frequency administration to provide frequency assignments and assignment of frequency channels to radio stations or systems, as well as to analyze electromagnetic compatibility between radiocommunication services.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Conducted EMI is caused by the physical contact of the conductors as opposed to radiated EMI which is caused by induction (without physical contact of the conductors).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] For lower frequencies, EMI is caused by conduction and, for higher frequencies, by radiation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] EMI through the ground wire is also very common in an electrical facility.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Interference tends to be more troublesome with older radio technologies such as analogue amplitude modulation, which have no way of distinguishing unwanted in-band signals from the intended signal, and the omnidirectional antennas used with broadcast systems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Newer radio systems incorporate several improvements that enhance the selectivity.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In digital radio systems, such as Wi-Fi, error-correction techniques can be used.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Spread-spectrum and frequency-hopping techniques can be used with both analogue and digital signalling to improve resistance to interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] A highly directional receiver, such as a parabolic antenna or a diversity receiver, can be used to select one signal in space to the exclusion of others.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The most extreme example of digital spread-spectrum signalling to date is ultra-wideband (UWB), which proposes the use of large sections of the radio spectrum at low amplitudes to transmit high-bandwidth digital data.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In the United States, the 1982 Public Law 97-259 allowed the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) to regulate the susceptibility of consumer electronic equipment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Potential sources of RFI and EMI include: various types of transmitters, doorbell transformers, toaster ovens, electric blankets, ultrasonic pest control devices, electric bug zappers, heating pads, and touch controlled lamps.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Multiple CRT computer monitors or televisions sitting too close to one another can sometimes cause a "shimmy" effect in each other, due to the electromagnetic nature of their picture tubes, especially when one of their de-gaussing coils is activated.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Electromagnetic interference at 2.4 GHz may be caused by 802.11b, 802.11g and 802.11n wireless devices, Bluetooth devices, baby monitors and cordless telephones, video senders, and microwave ovens.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Switching loads (inductive, capacitive, and resistive), such as electric motors, transformers, heaters, lamps, ballast, power supplies, etc., all cause electromagnetic interference especially at currents above 2 A.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The usual method used for suppressing EMI is by connecting a snubber network, a resistor in series with a capacitor, across a pair of contacts.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] While this may offer modest EMI reduction at very low currents, snubbers do not work at currents over 2 A with electromechanical contacts.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Another method for suppressing EMI is the use of ferrite core noise suppressors (or ferrite beads), which are inexpensive and which clip on to the power lead of the offending device or the compromised device.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Switched-mode power supplies can be a source of EMI, but have become less of a problem as design techniques have improved, such as integrated power factor correction.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Most countries have legal requirements that mandate electromagnetic compatibility: electronic and electrical hardware must still work correctly when subjected to certain amounts of EMI, and should not emit EMI, which could interfere with other equipment (such as radios).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Radio frequency signal quality has declined throughout the 21st century by roughly one decibel per year as the spectrum becomes increasingly crowded.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This has inflicted a Red Queen's race on the mobile phone industry as companies have been forced to put up more cellular towers (at new frequencies) that then cause more interference thereby requiring more investment by the providers and frequent upgrades of mobile phones to match.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These are civilian standards for domestic, commercial, industrial and automotive sectors.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These standards form the basis of other national or regional standards, most notably the European Norms (EN) written by CENELEC (European committee for electrotechnical standardisation).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] US organizations include the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), the American National Standards Institute (ANSI), and the US Military (MILSTD).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Integrated circuits are often a source of EMI, but they must usually couple their energy to larger objects such as heatsinks, circuit board planes and cables to radiate significantly.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] On integrated circuits, important means of reducing EMI are: the use of bypass or decoupling capacitors on each active device (connected across the power supply, as close to the device as possible), rise time control of high-speed signals using series resistors, and IC power supply pin filtering.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Shielding is usually a last resort after other techniques have failed, because of the added expense of shielding components such as conductive gaskets.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] At lower frequencies, such as 133 MHz, radiation is almost exclusively via I/O cables; RF noise gets onto the power planes and is coupled to the line drivers via the VCC and GND pins.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The RF is then coupled to the cable through the line driver as common-mode noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Since the noise is common-mode, shielding has very little effect, even with differential pairs.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The RF energy is capacitively coupled from the signal pair to the shield and the shield itself does the radiating.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] One cure for this is to use a braid-breaker or choke to reduce the common-mode signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] At higher frequencies, usually above 500 MHz, traces get electrically longer and higher above the plane.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Two techniques are used at these frequencies: wave shaping with series resistors and embedding the traces between the two planes.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] If all these measures still leave too much EMI, shielding such as RF gaskets and copper or conductive tape can be used.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Most digital equipment is designed with metal or conductive-coated plastic cases.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Any unshielded semiconductor (e.g. an integrated circuit) will tend to act as a detector for those radio signals commonly found in the domestic environment (e.g. mobile phones).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Such a detector can demodulate the high frequency mobile phone carrier (e.g., GSM850 and GSM1900, GSM900 and GSM1800) and produce low-frequency (e.g., 217 Hz) demodulated signals.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This demodulation manifests itself as unwanted audible buzz in audio appliances such as microphone amplifier, speaker amplifier, car radio, telephones etc.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Adding onboard EMI filters or special layout techniques can help in bypassing EMI or improving RF immunity.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Some ICs are designed (e.g., LMV831-LMV834, MAX9724) to have integrated RF filters or a special design that helps reduce any demodulation of high-frequency carrier.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Designers often need to carry out special tests for RF immunity of parts to be used in a system.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These tests are often done in an anechoic chamber with a controlled RF environment where the test vectors produce a RF field similar to that produced in an actual environment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Interference in radio astronomy, where it is commonly referred to as radio-frequency interference (RFI), is any source of transmission that is within the observed frequency band other than the celestial sources themselves.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Because transmitters on and around the Earth can be many times stronger than the astronomical signal of interest, RFI is a major concern for performing radio astronomy.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Some of the frequency bands that are very important for radio astronomy, such as the 21-cm HI line at 1420 MHz, are protected by regulation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] However, modern radio-astronomical observatories such as VLA, LOFAR, and ALMA have a very large bandwidth over which they can observe.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Techniques to deal with RFI range from filters in hardware to advanced algorithms in software.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] One way to deal with strong transmitters is to filter out the frequency of the source completely.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This is for example the case for the LOFAR observatory, which filters out the FM radio stations between 90 and 110 MHz.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] It is important to remove such strong sources of interference as soon as possible, because they might "saturate" the highly sensitive receivers (amplifiers and analogue-to-digital converters), which means that the received signal is stronger than the receiver can handle.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] However, filtering out a frequency band implies that these frequencies can never be observed with the instrument.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] A common technique to deal with RFI within the observed frequency bandwidth, is to employ RFI detection in software.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Such software can find samples in time, frequency or time-frequency space that are contaminated by an interfering source.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These samples are subsequently ignored in further analysis of the observed data.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] This process is often referred to as *data flagging*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Because most transmitters have a small bandwidth and are not continuously present such as lightning or citizens' band (CB) radio devices, most of the data remains available for the astronomical analysis.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] However, data flagging can not solve issues with continuous broad-band transmitters, such as windmills, digital video or digital audio transmitters.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Another way to manage RFI is to establish a radio quiet zone (RQZ).
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] RQZ is a well-defined area surrounding receivers that has special regulations to reduce RFI in favor of radio astronomy observations within the zone.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The regulations may include special management of spectrum and power flux or power flux-density limitations.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The controls within the zone may cover elements other than radio transmitters or radio devices.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These include aircraft controls and control of unintentional radiators such as industrial, scientific and medical devices, vehicles, and power lines.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The first RQZ for radio astronomy is United States National Radio Quiet Zone (NRQZ), established in 1958.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Prior to the introduction of Wi-Fi, one of the biggest applications of 5 GHz band was the Terminal Doppler Weather Radar.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The decision to use 5 GHz spectrum for Wi-Fi was finalized at the World Radiocommunication Conference in 2003; however, meteorological authorities were not involved in the process.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] The subsequent lax implementation and misconfiguration of DFS had caused significant disruption in weather radar operations in a number of countries around the world.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] In Hungary, the weather radar system was declared non-operational for more than a month.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Due to the severity of interference, South African weather services ended up abandoning C band operation, switching their radar network to S band.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Transmissions on adjacent bands to those used by passive remote sensing, such as weather satellites, have caused interference, sometimes significant.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] There is concern that adoption of insufficiently regulated 5G could produce major interference issues.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] Significant interference can impair numerical weather prediction performance and incur negative economic and public safety impacts.
[src:emc-design-embedded/electromagnetic-interference] These concerns led US Secretary of Commerce Wilbur Ross and NASA Administrator Jim Bridenstine in February 2019 to urge the FCC to cancel a proposed spectrum auction, which was rejected.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] A **Faraday cage** or **Faraday shield** is an enclosure used to block some electromagnetic fields.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] A Faraday shield may be formed by a continuous covering of conductive material, or in the case of a Faraday cage, by a mesh of such materials.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are named after the scientist Michael Faraday, who first constructed one in 1836.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Faraday cages work because an external electrical field will cause the electric charges within the cage's conducting material to be distributed in a way that cancels out the field's effect inside the cage.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] This phenomenon can be used to protect sensitive electronic equipment (for example RF receivers) from external radio frequency interference (RFI), often during testing or alignment of the device.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are also used to protect people and equipment against electric currents such as lightning strikes and electrostatic discharges, because the cage conducts electrical current around the outside of the enclosed space and none passes through the interior.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Faraday cages cannot block stable or slowly varying magnetic fields, such as the Earth's magnetic field (a compass will still work inside one).
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] To a large degree, however, they shield the interior from external electromagnetic radiation if the conductor is thick enough and any hole is significantly smaller than the wavelength of the radiation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] For example, certain computer forensic electronic systems test procedures that require an electromagnetic interference free environment can be carried out within a screened room.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] These rooms are spaces that are completely enclosed by one or more layers of a fine metal mesh or perforated sheet metal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The metal layers are grounded to dissipate any electric currents generated from external or internal electromagnetic fields, and thus they block a large amount of the electromagnetic interference (see also electromagnetic shielding).
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Near-field, high-powered frequency transmissions like HF RFID are more likely to penetrate.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Solid cages generally attenuate fields over a broader frequency range than mesh cages.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] In 1754, Jean-Antoine Nollet published an account of the cage effect in his *Leçons de physique expérimentale*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] In 1755, Benjamin Franklin observed the effect by lowering an uncharged cork ball suspended on a silk thread through an opening in an electrically charged metal can.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The behavior is that of a Faraday cage or shield.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] In 1836, Michael Faraday observed that the excess charge on a charged conductor resided only on its exterior and had no influence on anything enclosed within it.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] To demonstrate this, he built a metal foil-coated room and allowed high-voltage discharges from an electrostatic generator to strike the outside of the room.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] He used an electroscope to show that there was no electric charge present on the inside of the room walls.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] A continuous Faraday shield is a hollow conductor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Externally or internally applied electromagnetic fields produce forces on the charge carriers (usually electrons) within the conductor; the charges are redistributed accordingly due to electrostatic induction.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The redistributed charges greatly reduce the voltage within the surface, to an extent depending on the capacitance; however, full cancellation does not occur.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] If charge $+Q$ is placed inside an ungrounded Faraday shield without touching the walls, the internal face of the shield becomes charged with $-Q$ , leading to field lines originating at the charge and extending to charges inside the inner surface of the metal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The field line paths in this inside space (to the endpoint negative charges) are dependent on the shape of the inner containment walls.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Simultaneously $+Q$ accumulates on the outer face of the shield.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The spread of charges on the outer face is not affected by the position of the internal charge inside the enclosure, but rather determined by the shape of the outer face.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] So for all intents and purposes, the Faraday shield generates the same static electric field on the outside that it would generate if the metal were simply charged with $+Q$ .
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] See Faraday's ice pail experiment, for example, for more details on electric field lines and the decoupling of the outside from the inside.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Note that electromagnetic waves are not static charges.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] If the cage is grounded, the excess charges will be neutralized as the ground connection creates an equipotential bonding between the outside of the cage and the environment, so there is no voltage between them and therefore also no field.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The inner face and the inner charge will remain the same, so the field is kept inside.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Static electric shielding effectiveness is largely independent of the geometry of the conductive material; however, the static magnetic fields can penetrate the shield completely.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] In the case of varying electromagnetic fields, the faster the variations are (i.e., the higher the frequencies), the better the material resists magnetic field penetration.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] In this case, the shielding also depends on the electrical conductivity, the magnetic properties of the conductive materials used in the cages, as well as their thicknesses.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] A good example of the effectiveness of a Faraday shield can be obtained from considerations of skin depth.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] With skin depth, the current flowing is mostly on the surface and decays exponentially with depth through the material.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Because a Faraday shield has finite thickness, this determines how well the shield works; a thicker shield can attenuate electromagnetic fields better, and to a lower frequency.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Faraday cages are Faraday shields that have holes in them and are therefore more complex to analyze.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] The shorter the wavelength, the better it passes through a mesh of a given size.
[src:emc-design-embedded/faraday-cage] Thus, to work well at short wavelengths (i.e., high frequencies), the holes in the cage must be smaller than the wavelength of the incident wave.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] A **ferrite bead** – also called a **ferrite block**, **ferrite core**, **ferrite ring**, **EMI filter**, or **ferrite choke** – is a type of choke that suppresses high-frequency electronic noise in electronic circuits.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads employ high-frequency current dissipation in a ferrite ceramic to build high-frequency noise suppression devices.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads prevent electromagnetic interference (EMI) in two directions: *from* a device or *to* a device.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] A conductive cable acts as an antenna – if the device produces radio-frequency energy, this can be *transmitted* through the cable, which acts as an unintentional radiator.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] In this case, the bead is required for regulatory compliance to reduce EMI.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Conversely, if there are other sources of EMI, such as household appliances, the bead prevents the cable from acting as an antenna and *receiving* interference from these other devices.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] This is particularly common on data cables and medical equipment.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Large ferrite beads are commonly seen on external cabling.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] In addition, various smaller ferrite beads are used internally in circuits—on conductors or around the pins of small circuit-board components, such as transistors, connectors, and integrated circuits.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Beads can block low-level unintended radio frequency energy on wires intended to be DC conductors by acting as a low-pass filter.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] For example, on unbalanced coax transmission lines (such as video cables), the cable is designed to contain the signal, and beads can be used to block stray common mode current from using the cable as an antenna while not interfering with the signal carried inside the cable.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] In this use, the bead is a simple form of a balun.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are one of the simplest and least expensive interference filters to install on preexisting electronic cabling.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] For a simple ferrite ring, the wire is wrapped around the core through the center, typically five or seven times.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Clamp-on cores are also available, which attach without wrapping the wire: this type of ferrite core is usually designed so that the wire passes only once through it.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] If the fit is not snug enough, the core can be secured with cable ties, or if the center is large enough, the cabling can loop through one or more times.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] (However, although each loop increases the impedance to high frequencies, it also shifts the frequency of the highest impedance to a lower frequency.) Small ferrite beads can be slipped over component leads to suppress parasitic oscillation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Surface-mount ferrite beads are available.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Like any other surface-mount inductor, these are soldered into a gap in the printed circuit board trace.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Inside the bead component, a coil of wire runs between layers of ferrite to form a multi-turn inductor around the high-permeability core.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ferrite beads are used as a passive low-pass filter by dissipating radio frequency (RF) energy as heat by design.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors, on the other hand, have no resistance and hence do not dissipate energy as heat.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Ideal inductors only have inductive reactance, which reduces the flow of high-frequency signals by returning some of their energy back towards the signal source (possibly reducing the amount of power drawn) rather than dissipating that energy as heat (as done by the resistance in ferrite beads).
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] While an inductor's reactance may commonly be referred to simply as *impedance*, impedance generally can be any combination of resistance and reactance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] The geometry and electromagnetic properties of coiled wire over the ferrite bead result in an impedance for high-frequency signals, attenuating high-frequency EMI/RFI electronic noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] The energy is either reflected back up the cable or dissipated as low-level heat.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Only in extreme cases is the heat noticeable.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] A ferrite bead can be added to an inductor to improve, in two ways, its ability to block unwanted high frequency noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] First, the ferrite concentrates the magnetic field, increasing inductance and, therefore, reactance, which filters out the noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Second, if the ferrite is so designed, it can produce an additional loss in the form of resistance in the ferrite itself.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] The ferrite creates an inductor with a very low Q factor.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] This loss heats the ferrite, generally by a negligible amount.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] While the signal level is large enough to cause interference or undesirable effects in sensitive circuits, the energy blocked is typically relatively small.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Depending on the application, the resistive loss characteristic of the ferrite may or may not be desired.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] A design that uses a ferrite bead to improve noise filtering must consider specific circuit characteristics and the frequency range to block.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ferrite-bead] Different ferrite materials have different properties concerning frequency, and the manufacturer's literature helps select the most effective material for the frequency range.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In an electrical system, a **ground loop** or **earth loop** occurs when two points of a circuit are intended to have the same ground reference potential but instead have a different potential between them.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This is typically caused when enough current is flowing in the connection between the two ground points to produce a voltage drop and cause the two points to be at different potentials.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Current may be produced in a ground loop by electromagnetic induction.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loops are a major cause of noise, hum, and interference in audio, video, and computer systems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Wiring practices that protect against ground loops include ensuring that all vulnerable signal circuits are referenced to one point as ground.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The use of differential signaling can provide rejection of ground-induced interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The removal of ground connections to equipment in an effort to eliminate ground loops will also eliminate the protection the safety ground connection is intended to provide.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] A ground loop is caused by the interconnection of electrical devices that results in multiple paths to ground, thereby forming closed conductive loops through the ground connections.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] A common example is two electrical devices, each connected to a mains power outlet by a three-conductor cable and plug containing a protective ground conductor for safety.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] When signal cables are connected between both devices, the shield of the signal cable is typically connected to the grounded chassis of both devices.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This forms a closed loop through the ground conductors of the power cords, which are connected through the building wiring.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In the vicinity of electric power wiring, there will always be stray magnetic fields, particularly from utility lines oscillating at line frequency (50 or 60 hertz).
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] These ambient magnetic fields passing through the ground loop will induce a current in the loop by electromagnetic induction.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The ground loop acts as a single-turn secondary winding of a transformer, the primary being the summation of all current-carrying conductors nearby.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The amount of current induced will depend on the magnitude and proximity of nearby currents.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The presence of high-power equipment, such as industrial motors or transformers can increase the interference.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Since the conductors comprising the ground loop usually have very low resistance, often below one ohm, even weak magnetic fields can induce significant currents.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Since the ground conductor of the signal cable linking the two devices is part of the signal path of the cable, the alternating ground current flowing through the cable can introduce electrical interference in the signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The induced alternating current flowing through the resistance of the cable ground conductor will cause a small AC voltage drop across the cable ground.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This is added to the signal applied to the input of the next stage.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In audio equipment, the line frequency interference may be heard as a hum in the speakers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In a video system it may cause distortion or synchronization problems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In computer data connections, it can cause slowdowns or failures of data transfer.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loops can also exist within the internal circuits of electronic equipment, as design flaws.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The addition of signal interconnection cables to a system where equipment enclosures are already required to be bonded to ground can create ground loops.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Proper design of such a system will satisfy both safety grounding requirements and signal integrity.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] For this reason, in some large professional installations such as recording studios, it is sometimes the practice to provide two completely separate ground connections to equipment bays.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] One is the normal safety ground that connects to exposed metalwork, the other is a technical ground for cable screens and the like.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The circuit diagram illustrates a simple ground loop.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Circuit 1 (left) and circuit 2 (right) share a common path to ground of resistance $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ .
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Ideally, this ground conductor would have no resistance ( $\scriptstyle R_{G}=0$ ), yielding no voltage drop across it ( $\scriptstyle V_{G}=0$ ), keeping the connection point between the circuits at a constant ground potential.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In that case, the output of circuit 2 is simply $\scriptstyle V_{\text{out}}=V_{2}$ .
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] However, if this ground conductor has some resistance ( $\scriptstyle R_{G}>0$ ), then it forms a voltage divider with $\scriptstyle R_{1}$ .
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] As a result, if a current ( $\scriptstyle I_{1}$ ) is flowing through $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ from circuit 1, then a voltage drop across $\scriptstyle R_{G}$ of $\scriptstyle V_{G}\;=\;I_{1}R_{G}$ occurs, causing the shared ground connection to no longer be at the actual ground potential.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Thus, the two circuits are no longer isolated, and circuit 1 can introduce interference into the output of circuit 2.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] If circuit 2 is an audio system and circuit 1 has large AC currents flowing in it, the interference may be heard as a 50 or 60 Hz hum in the speakers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Also, both circuits have voltage $\scriptstyle V_{G}$ on their grounded parts that may be exposed to contact, possibly presenting a shock hazard.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This is true even if circuit 2 is turned off.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Although ground loops occur most often in the ground conductors of electrical equipment, similar loops can occur wherever two or more circuits share a common current path.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] If enough current flows, similar problems occur in these conditions.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] A common type of ground loop is due to faulty interconnections between electronic components, such as laboratory or recording studio equipment, or home component audio, video, and computer systems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This can create inadvertent closed loops in the ground wiring circuit, which can allow stray line frequency AC current to be induced and flow through the ground conductors of signal cables.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The voltage drops in the ground system caused by these currents are added to the signal path, introducing noise and hum into the output.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The loops can include the building's utility wiring ground system when more than one component is grounded through the protective earth (third wire) in their power cords.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The symptoms of a ground loop, ground noise and hum in electrical equipment are caused by current flowing in the ground or *shield* conductor of a cable.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] 1 shows a signal cable *S* linking two electronic components, including the typical line driver and receiver amplifiers *(triangles)*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The cable has a ground or shield conductor which is connected to the chassis ground of each component.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The driver amplifier in component 1 *(left)* applies signal *V*1 between the signal and ground conductors of the cable.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] At the destination end *(right)*, the signal and ground conductors are connected to a differential amplifier.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] If *I* is an AC current, this can result in noise added to the signal path in component 2.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The diagrams in this section show a typical ground loop caused by a signal cable *S* connecting two grounded electronic components *C1* and *C2*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The loop consists of the signal cable's ground conductor, which is connected through the components' metal chassis to the ground wires *P* in their power cords, which are plugged into outlet grounds that are connected through the building's utility ground wire system *G*.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The solution to ground loop noise is to break the ground loop or otherwise prevent the current from flowing.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] A hazardous technique sometimes used by amateurs is to break the *third wire* ground conductor *P* in one of the component's power cords, by removing the ground pin on the plug, or using a cheater plug.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This creates an electric shock hazard by leaving one of the components ungrounded.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] A more comprehensive solution is to use equipment that employs differential signaling.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Ground noise can only get into the signal path in single-ended signaling, in which the ground or shield conductor serves as one side of the signal path.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] When the signal is sent as a differential signal along a pair of wires, neither of which are connected to ground, any noise from the ground system induced in the signal lines is a common-mode signal, identical in both wires.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Since the line receiver at the destination end only responds to differential signals, a difference in voltage between the two lines, the common-mode noise is canceled out.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Thus these systems are very immune to electrical noise, including ground noise.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Professional and scientific equipment often uses differential signaling with balanced lines.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] So, when a current is induced in the loop, there will be a voltage drop along the signal ground return.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This is directly additive to the wanted signal and will result in objectionable hum.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] For instance, if a current I of 1 mA at the local power frequency is induced in the ground loop, and the resistance R of the screen of the signal cable is 100 mΩ, the voltage drop will be $V=I\cdot R$ = 100 μV.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This is a significant fraction of the output voltage of a moving coil pickup cartridge, and imposes an objectionable hum on the cartridge output.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Attempting to cure these problems by removing the protective ground conductor creates a shock hazard.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Solving hum problems must be done in the signal interconnections, and this is done in two main ways, which may be combined.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Isolation is the quickest, quietest and most foolproof method of resolving hum problems.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The signal is isolated by a small transformer, such that the source and destination equipment each retain their own protective ground connections, but there is no through connection from one to the other in the signal path.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] By transformer isolating all unbalanced connections, the unbalanced connections are converted to balanced connections.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In analog applications such as audio, the physical limitations of the transformers cause some signal degradation, by limiting bandwidth and adding some distortion.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Balanced connections see the spurious noise due to ground loop current as common-mode interference while the signal is differential, enabling them to be separated at the destination by circuits having a high common-mode rejection ratio.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This rejection can be accomplished with transformers or semiconductor output drivers and line receivers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] With the increasing trend towards digital processing and transmission of audio signals, the full range of isolation by small pulse transformers, optocouplers or fiber optics become more useful.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Standard protocols such as S/PDIF, AES3 or TOSLINK are available in relatively inexpensive equipment and allow full isolation, so ground loops need not arise, especially when connecting between audio systems and computers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In instrumentation systems, the use of differential inputs with high common-mode rejection ratio, to minimize the effects of induced AC signals on the parameter to be measured, is widespread.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] It may also be possible to introduce narrow notch filters at the power frequency and its lower harmonics; however, this can not be done in audio systems due to the objectionable audible effects on the wanted signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In analog video, mains hum can be seen as hum bars (bands of slightly different brightness) scrolling vertically up the screen.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] These are frequently seen with video projectors where the display device has its case grounded via a 3-prong plug, and the other components have a floating ground connected to the CATV coax.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In this situation the video cable is grounded at the projector end to the home electrical system, and at the other end to the cable TV's ground, inducing a current through the cable which distorts the picture.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The problem is best solved with an isolation transformer in the CATV RF feed, a feature included in some CATV box designs.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Ground loop issues with television coaxial cable can affect any connected audio device such as a receiver.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In digital systems, which commonly transmit data serially (RS-232, RS-485, USB, FireWire, DVI, HDMI etc.) the signal voltage is often much larger than induced power frequency AC on the connecting cable screens.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Of those protocols listed, only RS-232 is single-ended with ground return, but it is a large signal, typically + and - 12V, all the others being differential.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Differential signaling must use a balanced line to ensure that the signal does not radiate and that induced noise from a ground loop is a common-mode signal and can be removed at the differential receiver.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Many data communications systems such as Ethernet 10BASE-T, 100BASE-TX and 1000BASE-T, use DC-balanced encoding such as Manchester code.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] The ground loop(s) which would occur in most installations are avoided by using signal-isolating transformers.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Other systems break the ground loop at data frequencies by fitting small ferrite beads around the connecting cables near each end or just inside the equipment boundary.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] These form a common-mode choke which inhibits unbalanced current flow, without affecting the differential signal.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Coaxial cables used at radio frequencies may be wound several times through a ferrite bead to add a useful amount of common-mode inductance.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] This limits the flow of unwanted high-frequency common-mode current along the cable shield.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Where no power need be transmitted, only digital data, the use of fiber optics can remove many ground loop problems, and sometimes safety problems too.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Optical isolators or optocouplers are frequently used to provide ground loop isolation, and often safety isolation and can help prevent fault propagation.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Generally, the analog and digital parts of the circuit are in separate areas of the PCB, with their own ground planes to obtain the necessary low inductance grounding and avoid ground bounce.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] These are tied together at a carefully chosen star point.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Where analog-to-digital converters (ADCs) are in use, the star point may have to be at or very close to the ground terminals of the ADC(s).
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Phase lock loop circuits are particularly vulnerable because the VCO loop filter circuit is working with sub-microvolt signals when the loop is locked, and any disturbance will cause frequency jitter and possible loss of lock.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] Grounding and the potential for ground loops are also important considerations in circuit design.
[src:emc-design-embedded/ground-loop-electricity] In many circuits, large currents may exist through the ground plane, leading to voltage differences of the ground reference in different parts of the circuit, which can lead to hum and other problems.
